1 appr aiser who could reasonably be perceived to act as a
2 disinterested third party in rendering an unbiased real property
3 valuation must perform assignments with impartiality, objectivity
4 and independence and without accommodation of personal interests;
5 2. The acceptance of compensation that is contingent upon the
6 reporting of a predetermined value or a direction in value that
7 favors the cause of the client, the amount of the value estimate,
8 the attainment of a stipulated result or the occurrence of a
9 subsequent event is unethical;
10 3. The payment of undisclosed fees, commissions or things of
11 value in connection with the procurement of real property valuation
12 assignments is unethical;
13 4. When providing residential appraisal services, an invoice
14 for service exhibiting compensation to the appraiser must be
15 included as the first page in all assignments;
16 4. 5. Advertising for or soliciting appraisal assignments in a
17 manner which is false, misleading or exaggerated is unethical;
18 5. 6. An appraiser must protect the confidential nature of the
19 appraiser-client relationship; and
20 6. 7. Using or attempting to use the seal, certificate, or
21 license of another as their own; falsely impersonating any duly
22 licensed appraiser; using or attempting to use an inactive, expired,
23 suspended, or revoked license; or aiding or abetting any of the
24 foregoing is unethical.
